{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cc5ebfe9-f97d-4104-85b0-b8fbe2eb2bc4","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\nMSTest v4 changed the **test ID generation strategy**. The default switched from `DisplayName` to `FullyQualified`, so Azure DevOps sees every test as a new test. To restore history, add this to your project:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is **no longer tied to any specific test** — it's a class-level context. Accessing `TestName` now throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it happened to return the first test's name, but that was never reliable.\n\nYour `SetupTests.cs` hits this exactly on line 13. Fix by guarding or removing the access:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_012fykVef2sCFxDKeaDXQUJs","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-e727551039bb4e3ca6e477e4b10dc7ff/SetupTests.cs","old_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        var testName = context.TestName;\n        // Log setup for specific test\n    }","new_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        // In MSTest v4 the ClassInitialize context is class-scoped;\n        // TestName is only available in [TestInitialize] or test methods.\n        context.WriteLine(\"ClassInit running for \" + context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName);\n    }"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-e727551039bb4e3ca6e477e4b10dc7ff/SetupTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"5880d725-a0f8-4087-bb04-ddc5fc528166","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a thorough answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Fully Qualified Test Names (FQN) changed** — MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed. The default `TestIdGenerationStrategy` changed, which means Azure DevOps sees them as entirely new tests (no history linkage). This is why all tests appear as \"brand new.\"\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is no longer associated with any specific test. Accessing `TestContext.TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException` because at class-initialization time, no test has started yet. In v3, this happened to work (it returned the name of the first test being run), but it was never a reliable/documented behavior.\n\n\n3. There are several other breaking changes worth noting: `DataRow` attributes now require wrapping null values in an object array, `DeploymentItem` behavior has shifted, `TestContext.Properties` became read-only in certain scenarios, class and assembly cleanup timing changed, and `ExpectedException` attribute behavior may differ from previous versions.","outputTokens":811,"requestId":"1BD2:2912D8:BED6C6:D75BBE:6A03F1CE"},"id":"11c02b6f-e4f4-47f9-83f2-b80d9e5683ed","timestamp":"2026-05-13T03:37:03.941Z","parentId":"3564ba18-14eb-469c-be0a-05065b9eadfc"}
{"type":"tool.execution_start","data":{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_012fykVef2sCFxDKeaDXQUJs","toolName":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-e727551039bb4e3ca6e477e4b10dc7ff/SetupTests.cs","old_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        var testName = context.TestName;\n        // Log setup for specific test\n    }","new_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        // In MSTest v4 the ClassInitialize context is class-scoped;\n        // TestName is only available in [TestInitialize] or test methods.\n        context.WriteLine(\"ClassInit running for \" + context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName);\n    }"}},"id":"e584198d-432d-437e-bfde-c1e7343cd3d3","timestamp":"2026-05-13T03:37:03.942Z","parentId":"11c02b6f-e4f4-47f9-83f2-b80d9e5683ed"}
